The Curse of Dimensionality (Richard Bellman):

  1. In machine learning world, it refers to the scenario when the number of dimensionality (features, input variables, factors) increases, the performance of our algorithm will deteriorate, especially for those algorithms which couldnt scale well (such as KNN, clustering algorithms rely on distance calculations)
  2. Mathematically speaking, the problem is that when the dimensionality increases, the volume of the space increases so fast that the available data become sparse. quote from Wikipedia

  3. Graphical explaination

    • Finding treasure in the high dimension space ( with D dimensions each dimension has M states, we will have \(M^D\) possible combinations. This number exponentially grows)

    • Hypercube

      • A hypercube is a generalization of a cube to an arbitrary number of dimensions. When p = 1, a hypercube is simply a line segment, when p = 2 it is a square, and when p = 100 it is a 100-dimensional cube. - from ISLR Sixth p182

      • sampling density is the number of samples per unit distance. sampling density is proportional to \((Num of Observations)^\frac{1}{D}\)

      • Now suppose that we wish to make a prediction for a test observation by creating a p-dimensional hypercube centered around the test observation that contains, on average, 10 % of the training observations. Features along each dimension is uniformly (evenly) distributed on [0, 1]. For p = 1,2, and 100, what is the length of each side of the hypercube? - from ISLR Sixth p182

        • p = 1, L = \(\frac{1}{10}\) = 0.1

        • p = 2, L = \((\frac{1}{10})^\frac{1}{2}\) = 0.32

        • p = 100, L = \((\frac{1}{10})^\frac{1}{100}\) = 0.98

Approaches to tackle the curse of dimensionality

  1. Increasing the number of observations
  2. Reducing the number of dimensions ( more pragmatic solution)
  • Feature Selection - select a subset of the original set of features
    • i.e.Regularized Regression has the built-in feature selection
  • Feature Extraction - create a new, smaller set of features out of the original set
    • PCA (Principlal Component Analysis)
    • LDA (Linear Discriminant Analysis)

PCA (Principal Component Analysis)

  1. General fundamentals:
  • Unsupervised Algorithm
  • New set of features are the linear combination of the original features
  • New features are orthogonal ( meaning that they are uncorrelated)
  • The rank of the PCs are according to their explained variance (The first principal component (PC1) explains the most variance in your dataset; PC2 explains the second most variance, and so on)
  • Dimensionality is reduced by limiting the number of PCs to keep based on cumulative explained variance
  • Normalize the dataset, before applying PCA
  1. Visual summary (borrowed from this site):
  1. Deeper view ( mathematical view )
  • Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)

    • Here is a good starting point from Wikipedia

    • U is mxm square matrix - Unitary matrix
    • V is nxn sqaure matrix - Unitary matrix
    • \(\sum\) is diagonal matrix

    • Exists for all X matrices

  • Eigen Decomposition
    • put together the set of eigenvectors of A in a matrix denoted U. Each column of U is an eigenvector of A. The eigenvalues are stored in a diagonal matrix (denoted ), where the diagonal elements gives the eigenvalues (and all the other values are zeros)

    \(AU = U\Lambda\)
    \(A = U{\Lambda}U^{-1}\)

    • Not all matrices have Eigen decomposition
    • Postitive semi definite matrices always have Eigen decompostion. A matrix is said to be positive semi-definite when it can be obtained as the product of a matrix by its transpose. Thus, they are symmetric.

    • The important properties of a positive semi-definite matrix is that its eigenvalues are always positive or null, and that its eigenvectors are pairwise orthogonal when their eigenvalues are different. Thus U is Orthogonal Matrix

    • Covariance Matrix

    \[cov_{x,y} = \frac{\sum\limits_{i=1}^{n}{(x_i-\overline{x}) \cdot (x_i-\overline{x})} }{n-1}\] \[cov = \frac{XX^T}{n-1}\]

    • How Eigen decomposition relates to SVD

    \(XX^TU = U{\sum}^2U^TU\)

    \(XX^TU = U{\sum}^2\)
    • The columns of U are eigenvectors of \(X\)\(\times\)\(X^T\)
    • The columns of V are eigenvectors of \(X^T\)\(\times\)\(X\)
    • The non-zero elements of (non-zero singular values) are the square roots of the non-zero eigenvalues of \(X\)\(\times\)\(X^T\) or \(X^T\)\(\times\)\(X\)

Some basic terminologies found here:

  • Unit Vectors: vectors of length 1, sometimes also called direction vectors \(\hat{v}\) = \(\frac{v}{|v|}\)
  • Orthogonal Vectors: Two vectors u and v whose dot product is uv=0 are said to be orthogonal.
  • Orthonormal Vectors: Unit vectors which are orthogonal are said to be orthonormal.

  • Orthogonal Matrix: \(U^T = U^{-1}\)

    \(U^T\)\(\times\)U = U\(\times\)\(U^T\) = \(I\)

    (Calculating \(U^{-1}\) is computationally expensive O(\(N^3\)), while calculating \(U^T\) is cheap O(\(N^2\)))

  • Eigen Vector/Eigen Values: 3Blue1Brown Linear Algebra Series

    Av= \(\lambda\)v

    • A is sqaure matrix
    • v is column vector which is eigenvector
    • \(\lambda\) is scalar which is eigenvalue

R PCA functions

  • princomp() - uses Eigen decomposition approach
  • prcomp() - uses SVD approach
# function for checking if packages have been installed and installing needed packages
installpkg <- function(x){
    if(x %in% rownames(installed.packages())==FALSE) {
        if(x %in% rownames(available.packages())==FALSE) {
            paste(x,"is not a valid package - please check again...")
        } else {
            install.packages(x)           
        }

    } else {
        paste(x,"package already installed...")
    }
}

# install necessary packages

installpkg("factoextra")

Use scree plot to show the percentage of variances explained by each principal component.

#fviz_eig(pca.whs)
fviz_screeplot(pca.whs, ncp=10)

Use variable loading matrix (columns are eigenvectors) prcomp()$rotation to show variables in PC1 dimension.

  • Loadings show the correlation between a variable and a PC.
  • Positive correlated variables point to the right side of the plot and negative correlated variables point to the left side.
sort(abs(pca.whs$rotation[,1]),decreasing=TRUE)[1:10]

Use the cosine square of the individuals (observations) on the PCs to show individuals.

  • \(\theta\) is the angle between the principal plane and vector \(x_i\)
  • cosine(\(\theta\)) can be used as the measure of an individual representation quality. If the value is large, \(x_i\) is close to the plane.
whs.ind <- get_pca_ind(pca.whs)
